Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is K-means clustering?
AI Response

K-means partitions data into K clusters by iteratively assigning points to the nearest centroid and updating
centroids as the mean of assigned points, minimizing intra-cluster variance.

Example 1.2

User

What is the softmax function?
AI Response

Softmax converts a vector of raw scores (logits) into probabilities that sum to 1, typically used as the final
activation in multi-class classification models.

Example 1.3

User

What is a transformer model?
AI Response

A transformer is a deep learning architecture using self-attention mechanisms that process all tokens in
parallel, enabling efficient NLP. GPT and BERT are transformer-based models.

Example 1.4

User

What is reinforcement learning?
AI Response

Reinforcement learning trains an agent to make decisions by interacting with an environment and receiving
rewards or penalties, aiming to maximize cumulative reward over time.

Example 1.5

User

What is word embedding?
AI Response

Word embeddings map words to dense vectors where similar words are nearby. Word2Vec, GloVe, and
FastText are popular methods, used as NLP model input features.

Example 1.6

User

What is transfer learning?
AI Response

Transfer learning reuses a model trained on one task as a starting point for another related task, reducing
training time and data requirements significantly.

Example 1.7

User

What is attention mechanism?
AI Response



Attention allows a model to focus on relevant input parts during output generation. Self-attention in
transformers computes weighted relationships between all token pairs.

Example 1.8

User

What is an RNN?
AI Response

A Recurrent Neural Network processes sequential data with loops allowing information to persist. LSTMs and
GRUs are variants that address the vanishing gradient problem.

Example 1.9

User

What is a convolutional neural network?
AI Response

A CNN uses convolutional layers to automatically learn spatial features from images. Pooling layers reduce
dimensionality. CNNs are the standard for image classification and detection tasks.

Example 1.10

User

What is mean squared error?
AI Response

MSE is (1/n) * sum of (predicted - actual)^2. It penalizes large errors heavily and is a standard loss function
for regression tasks, sensitive to outliers.



